832. quia, not quod, see on v. 834. merito tuo, cf. v. 7 37. 837. si esse te hilarum uidero. Fleckeisen transposed te esse but the change is not necessary. He also bracketed the esse in the second half of the line, in which editors have generally followed him.

838. ut quasi dies si dicta sit. The legal phrase diem dicere to fix a date for someone's appearance in court, hence ‘to accuse.⁷ Cf. Cure. 5 si status condictus cum lzosle inter- cedit dies, and Cic. Off. Ι. 12. 37 from XII Tabl. Argyrippus looks as gloomy as if he had to appear in court.

aorist, used as subj. Cf. capsim, axim, faxim and occupassit v. 818 and note on v. 467,

840. em aspecta, rideo, ‘there! look ! I’m laughing.’ Cf. Bacch. 102 3 em specta, tum scies, Pseud. 890 em ! illic habito ego.

841. utinam male qui mihi uolunt sic rideant. ‘O ! that my ill-wishers may laugh like that,' i.e. alienis malis rideant. Cf. Ter. Eun. 65 5 utinam sic sint qui mihi male uolunt.

842. me tu tristem credas tibi, ‘why you think I’m gloomy to you‚' i.e. ‘gloomy in my bear- ing towards you.'
